<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06312111 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06312111 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SAN-JOSE; COMPANY; WATER; SALE; COST; INCREASE  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  The price of water is going up nearly $2 a month on average for the 203,000customers of the San Jose Water Co.;   The rate hike, for one year only, wasapproved by the California Public Utilities Commission to allow the watercompany to recover most of the money it lost because of mandatory waterrationing in drought-stricken Santa Clara County.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  PUC RATE INCREASE ADDS $2 TO MONTHLY S.J. WATERBILLS  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The rate increase, which went into effect Wednesday, boosts the cost ofwater to consumers by 11.3 cents per 100 cubic feet, or 748 gallons, to $1.38.The basic monthly service charge is unchanged.;   According to water companyspokeswoman Sharon Whaley, this will add an average of $1.92 per month to the$26 bill of the typical residential customer.;   The money will allow thewater company to recoup about $5,217,000, about 75 percent of the revenue itlost between Aug. 9, 1990, and Aug. 31 of this year, because of mandatorywater rationing.;   The San Jose Water Co. is the largest retailer in thecounty, serving customers in Campbell, Los Gatos, Monte Sereno, Saratoga, andparts of Cupertino and San Jose.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff Report  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911107  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  183  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday, November 7, 199100312111,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>